<div class="container" style="max-width: 900px;">
    <h2 class="mb-3"><i class="bi bi-book"></i> Research Paper Writing Guide</h2>
    <p class="text-muted mb-4">
        Tips and strategies for writing each section of your research paper.
        Based on academic writing best practices.
    </p>

    <!-- Quick Navigation -->
    <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
            <strong>Jump to:</strong>
            <a href="#general" class="badge bg-dark text-decoration-none ms-1">General Tips</a>
            <a href="#introduction" class="badge bg-primary text-decoration-none ms-1">Introduction</a>
            <a href="#thesis" class="badge bg-primary text-decoration-none ms-1">Thesis Statement</a>
            <a href="#literature" class="badge bg-primary text-decoration-none ms-1">Literature Review</a>
            <a href="#body" class="badge bg-primary text-decoration-none ms-1">Body Paragraphs</a>
            <a href="#counter" class="badge bg-primary text-decoration-none ms-1">Counter-Arguments</a>
            <a href="#conclusion" class="badge bg-primary text-decoration-none ms-1">Conclusion</a>
            <a href="#references" class="badge bg-primary text-decoration-none ms-1">References</a>
            <a href="#apa7" class="badge bg-success text-decoration-none ms-1">APA 7 Format</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- General Tips -->
    <div class="card mb-3" id="general">
        <div class="card-header bg-dark text-white">
            <h5 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-lightbulb"></i> General Research Paper Tips</h5>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h6 class="fw-bold">Before You Write</h6>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Understand the assignment</strong> &mdash; Read the prompt carefully. Identify the required length, format, and citation style.</li>
                        <li><strong>Choose a focused topic</strong> &mdash; A narrow topic is easier to research and argue than a broad one. "Climate change" is too broad; "the effect of urban green spaces on local temperature" is focused.</li>
                        <li><strong>Research first, write second</strong> &mdash; Gather 8-12 credible sources before you start writing. Use academic databases like Google Scholar, JSTOR, or your library's resources.</li>
                        <li><strong>Create an outline</strong> &mdash; Map your argument before writing full paragraphs. This saves time and prevents writer's block.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h6 class="fw-bold">While You Write</h6>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Write the body first</strong> &mdash; Don't start with the introduction. Write your argument first, then introduce it.</li>
                        <li><strong>One idea per paragraph</strong> &mdash; Each paragraph should have a clear topic sentence and focus on a single point.</li>
                        <li><strong>Cite as you go</strong> &mdash; Don't leave citations for later. Add them while writing to avoid accidental plagiarism.</li>
                        <li><strong>Use academic tone</strong> &mdash; Avoid contractions, slang, and first person (unless your instructor allows it). Be precise and objective.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <h6 class="fw-bold mt-3">After You Write</h6>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Revise for argument</strong> &mdash; Does each paragraph support your thesis? Cut anything that doesn't.</li>
                        <li><strong>Proofread separately</strong> &mdash; Read once for content, once for grammar, once for citations.</li>
                        <li><strong>Read aloud</strong> &mdash; This catches awkward phrasing and run-on sentences.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Introduction -->
    <div class="card mb-3" id="introduction">
        <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
            <h5 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-door-open"></i> Introduction</h5>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Hook the reader, provide context, and present your thesis statement.</p>

            <h6 class="fw-bold">Structure (Funnel Approach)</h6>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Hook</strong> &mdash; Start with something attention-grabbing: a surprising statistic, a provocative question, a brief anecdote, or a bold statement.</li>
                <li><strong>Context</strong> &mdash; Provide background information that helps the reader understand your topic. Move from general to specific.</li>
                <li><strong>Significance</strong> &mdash; Explain why this topic matters. Who cares? What's at stake?</li>
                <li><strong>Thesis Statement</strong> &mdash; End with a clear, arguable claim that previews your main argument.</li>
            </ol>

            <div class="alert alert-warning mt-3 mb-0">
                <strong>Common Mistakes:</strong>
                <ul class="mb-0 mt-1">
                    <li>Starting with a dictionary definition ("Webster's defines X as...")</li>
                    <li>Being too broad or vague</li>
                    <li>Announcing your paper: "In this paper I will discuss..." &mdash; just discuss it</li>
                    <li>Including evidence or detailed arguments (save those for the body)</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Thesis Statement -->
    <div class="card mb-3" id="thesis">
        <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
            <h5 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-bullseye"></i> Thesis Statement / Main Argument</h5>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Your thesis is the central claim your entire paper supports. It's the backbone of your argument.</p>

            <h6 class="fw-bold">A Strong Thesis Is:</h6>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Specific</strong> &mdash; Not "Social media is bad" but "Excessive social media use among teens correlates with increased anxiety due to social comparison and sleep disruption."</li>
                <li><strong>Debatable</strong> &mdash; Someone should be able to reasonably disagree with it.</li>
                <li><strong>Supportable</strong> &mdash; You can back it up with evidence from your research.</li>
                <li><strong>Focused</strong> &mdash; It addresses a manageable scope for your paper length.</li>
            </ul>

            <h6 class="fw-bold mt-3">Thesis Formula</h6>
            <div class="bg-light p-3 rounded">
                <code>[Topic] + [Your Position] + [Because/Due to] + [Reasons 1, 2, 3]</code>
                <br /><br />
                <em>Example: "Universities should require media literacy courses because students lack critical evaluation skills, misinformation spreads rapidly on campus, and digital literacy improves academic performance."</em>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Literature Review -->
    <div class="card mb-3" id="literature">
        <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
            <h5 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-journal-bookmark"></i> Literature Review</h5>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Summarize, synthesize, and critically evaluate existing research on your topic.</p>

            <h6 class="fw-bold">Key Strategies</h6>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Organize by theme, not by source</strong> &mdash; Don't write "Smith says X. Jones says Y. Lee says Z." Instead, group related findings: "Multiple studies confirm that... (Smith, 2019; Jones, 2020; Lee, 2021)."</li>
                <li><strong>Synthesize, don't just summarize</strong> &mdash; Show how sources relate to each other. Where do they agree? Disagree? What patterns emerge?</li>
                <li><strong>Be critical</strong> &mdash; Evaluate the quality of each study. Note limitations, biases, or methodological weaknesses.</li>
                <li><strong>Identify the gap</strong> &mdash; End by showing what's missing in the research &mdash; this is what your paper addresses.</li>
            </ul>

            <h6 class="fw-bold mt-3">Useful Signal Phrases</h6>
            <div class="bg-light p-3 rounded">
                <ul class="mb-0">
                    <li>"According to Smith (2020), ..."</li>
                    <li>"Research suggests that ... (Jones, 2019)."</li>
                    <li>"While Lee (2021) argues X, Chen (2022) found that ..."</li>
                    <li>"Several studies have demonstrated ... (Author1, Year; Author2, Year)."</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Body Paragraphs -->
    <div class="card mb-3" id="body">
        <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
            <h5 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-text-paragraph"></i> Body Paragraphs</h5>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Present your evidence and analysis. Each paragraph should advance your argument.</p>

            <h6 class="fw-bold">The PIE Method</h6>
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-md-4">
                    <div class="card bg-light h-100">
                        <div class="card-body text-center">
                            <h6 class="fw-bold text-primary">P &mdash; Point</h6>
                            <p class="small mb-0">Start with a topic sentence that states the paragraph's main idea and connects to your thesis.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-4">
                    <div class="card bg-light h-100">
                        <div class="card-body text-center">
                            <h6 class="fw-bold text-primary">I &mdash; Illustration</h6>
                            <p class="small mb-0">Provide evidence: quotes, data, statistics, examples, or expert opinions. Always cite your sources.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-4">
                    <div class="card bg-light h-100">
                        <div class="card-body text-center">
                            <h6 class="fw-bold text-primary">E &mdash; Explanation</h6>
                            <p class="small mb-0">Analyze the evidence. Explain WHY it supports your point. This is where YOUR voice matters most.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h6 class="fw-bold mt-3">Transition Words</h6>
            <div class="bg-light p-3 rounded">
                <strong>To add:</strong> furthermore, moreover, additionally, in addition<br />
                <strong>To contrast:</strong> however, conversely, on the other hand, nevertheless<br />
                <strong>To show cause:</strong> therefore, consequently, as a result, thus<br />
                <strong>To give examples:</strong> for instance, specifically, to illustrate, such as
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Counter-Arguments -->
    <div class="card mb-3" id="counter">
        <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
            <h5 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-arrow-left-right"></i> Counter-Arguments &amp; Rebuttals</h5>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Show you've considered other perspectives, then explain why your position is stronger.</p>

            <h6 class="fw-bold">Why Include Counter-Arguments?</h6>
            <ul>
                <li>Shows intellectual honesty and critical thinking</li>
                <li>Strengthens your credibility with the reader</li>
                <li>Makes your argument more persuasive by addressing potential objections</li>
            </ul>

            <h6 class="fw-bold">How to Structure</h6>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Introduce the opposing view</strong> &mdash; "Critics argue that..." or "Some scholars contend..."</li>
                <li><strong>Present it fairly</strong> &mdash; Use the strongest version of the argument (steel-man, not straw-man).</li>
                <li><strong>Refute with evidence</strong> &mdash; Explain why the counterargument is flawed, incomplete, or outweighed by your evidence.</li>
                <li><strong>Concede if appropriate</strong> &mdash; "While it is true that X, this does not negate Y because..."</li>
            </ol>

            <div class="alert alert-info mb-0">
                <strong>Tip:</strong> Place your strongest rebuttal last. End this section by reinforcing why your position is the most compelling.
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Conclusion -->
    <div class="card mb-3" id="conclusion">
        <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
            <h5 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-flag"></i> Conclusion</h5>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Synthesize your argument and leave a lasting impression. Don't just repeat &mdash; elevate.</p>

            <h6 class="fw-bold">Structure</h6>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Restate your thesis</strong> &mdash; Rephrase it in new words, with the confidence of someone who has proved it.</li>
                <li><strong>Summarize key evidence</strong> &mdash; Brief reminders of your strongest points (1-2 sentences).</li>
                <li><strong>Broader implications</strong> &mdash; Why does this matter beyond your paper? What are the real-world consequences?</li>
                <li><strong>Closing statement</strong> &mdash; End with a call to action, a thought-provoking question, or a powerful final image.</li>
            </ol>

            <div class="alert alert-warning mt-3 mb-0">
                <strong>Avoid:</strong>
                <ul class="mb-0 mt-1">
                    <li>Introducing new evidence or arguments</li>
                    <li>Starting with "In conclusion..." (just conclude)</li>
                    <li>Simply copy-pasting your introduction</li>
                    <li>Being apologetic: "I may not be an expert, but..."</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- References -->
    <div class="card mb-3" id="references">
        <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
            <h5 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-bookmark"></i> References &amp; Citations</h5>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Give credit to your sources and allow readers to verify your claims.</p>

            <h6 class="fw-bold">Best Practices</h6>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Cite as you write</strong> &mdash; Never leave citations for later. Add them immediately to avoid plagiarism.</li>
                <li><strong>Use credible sources</strong> &mdash; Peer-reviewed journals, academic books, government reports, reputable news outlets.</li>
                <li><strong>Avoid over-quoting</strong> &mdash; Paraphrase more than you quote. Direct quotes should be reserved for powerful statements that can't be rephrased.</li>
                <li><strong>Check every citation</strong> &mdash; Make sure every in-text citation has a matching reference list entry, and vice versa.</li>
            </ul>

            <h6 class="fw-bold mt-3">When to Cite</h6>
            <div class="bg-light p-3 rounded">
                <ul class="mb-0">
                    <li>Direct quotes (always)</li>
                    <li>Paraphrased ideas from a source</li>
                    <li>Statistics, data, or specific facts</li>
                    <li>Theories, models, or frameworks</li>
                    <li>Claims that aren't common knowledge</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- APA 7 Quick Reference -->
    <div class="card mb-4" id="apa7">
        <div class="card-header bg-success text-white">
            <h5 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-file-text"></i> APA 7th Edition Quick Reference</h5>
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h6 class="fw-bold">Formatting Rules</h6>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Font:</strong> 12 pt Times New Roman, 11 pt Calibri, 11 pt Arial, or 10 pt Lucida Sans Unicode</li>
                        <li><strong>Spacing:</strong> Double-spaced throughout, including references</li>
                        <li><strong>Margins:</strong> 1 inch on all sides</li>
                        <li><strong>Page numbers:</strong> Top-right corner, starting on title page</li>
                        <li><strong>Indentation:</strong> First line of each paragraph indented 0.5 inch</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h6 class="fw-bold mt-3">Student vs Professional</h6>
                    <table class="table table-sm table-bordered">
                        <thead class="table-light">
                            <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Student</th><th>Professional</th></tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td>Running head</td><td>No</td><td>Yes (shortened title, ALL CAPS)</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Author note</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Title page info</td><td>Course, instructor, date</td><td>Author affiliations, ORCID</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Abstract</td><td>Only if required</td><td>Required (150-250 words)</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <h6 class="fw-bold">Heading Levels</h6>
                    <table class="table table-sm table-bordered">
                        <thead class="table-light">
                            <tr><th>Level</th><th>Format</th></tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td>1</td><td>Centered, Bold, Title Case</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>2</td><td>Left-Aligned, Bold, Title Case</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>3</td><td>Left-Aligned, Bold Italic, Title Case</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>4</td><td>Indented, Bold, Title Case, Period. Text continues...</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>5</td><td>Indented, Bold Italic, Title Case, Period. Text continues...</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>

                    <h6 class="fw-bold mt-3">In-Text Citations</h6>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>1 author:</strong> (Smith, 2020)</li>
                        <li><strong>2 authors:</strong> (Smith & Jones, 2020)</li>
                        <li><strong>3+ authors:</strong> (Smith et al., 2020)</li>
                        <li><strong>No author:</strong> ("Shortened Title," 2020)</li>
                        <li><strong>No date:</strong> (Smith, n.d.)</li>
                        <li><strong>Direct quote:</strong> (Smith, 2020, p. 45)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
